In 1987, I was bar hopping late at night with a person I thought was my 
friend & another stranger. We stopped between bars to smoke a joint. After 
we finished, my "friend" started to beat up the stranger for no reason. 
Near the end of this beating I told him to stop before he killed the guy. 
(he was kicking him in the head.) He pulled out a knife (a 5 inch 
stiletto) & asked me "who's gonna stop me?" I said I would if he didn't 
stop. He kept repeating "I'm bad, I'm bad" while swinging the knife in 
front of me. He cornered me between a building & himself & stabbed me. 
Turning the knife as it thrusted inside me. He then saw the stranger who 
was on the ground trying to crawl away. He went towards him (about 20 yards 
away) & said; "You're not going anywhere." That was my opportunity to 
escape. I put my hand on the wound & started running as fast as I could, 
screaming bloody murder as I ran. That saved my life.﻿

I'm going to be honest: it was fortunate for that baby that he was stabbed 
when he was a baby.

NOW, BEFORE YOU RAGE, here me out: infants, toddlers, and children have 
much higher healing potential than adults do, because they're so young. 
Since most babies bones are actually cartilage at birth, the younger the 
child, the easier it is to heal from injuries such as trips, slips, falls, 
open wounds and broken bones.

When I was around 5, I ended up falling off some playground equipment and 
breaking my left leg in a spiral fracture. The doctor told my mom that, had 
I been an adult, it would have taken 8 months to heal, because it had 
pretty much broken every bone from my knee to my ankle in multiple places. 
As it stood, I ended up having to wear a cast for 8 weeks, and got some 
pretty serious carpet burn from all the crawling I had to do (I was still 5 
years old, cut me some slack).

The point I make is this: Had this baby been an adult, the odds of him 
surviving would have probably been non-existent, but because he was a baby, 
that increased his odds of survival, thanks to the super-healing nature of 
his young body.
